AGI - A prominent representative of the Turkish opposition, the mayor of Istanbul Ekrem Imamoglu was re-elected with a large majority last night, with a victory that directs him towards the race for the Turkish presidential elections of 2028. Imamoglu's reconfirm now paves the way for a more pluralistic system, but also for a presidential candidacy which at this point seems inevitable. If Erdogan, as he made it clear, did not appear in 2028, the presidency race would start from a completely different scenario than last year: this time it would be the party of Erdogan, Akp, to have to look for a candidate, while Imamoglu would be the natural leader of the opposition. A scenario that would see the first citizen of Istanbul overwhelmed to lead the country, especially if Erdogan had to withdraw from the political scene. Almost unknown until 2019 to voters and members of the Republican People's Party (Chp), Imamoglu put an end to 25 years of rule of Erdogan and his field on the largest city in the country.
&nbsp;
"Today you opened the doors to a new future. From tomorrow Turkey will be another Turkey!", said the mayor last night, while a crowd of supporters celebrated his re-election in front of the municipality of Istanbul. Charismatic and medial personality, the fifty-year-old from subtle glasses and without frame is in the sight of power: at the end of 2022, he was sentenced to two years and seven months in prison for "insults" to members of the Turkish High Election Committee. Imamoglu appealed, but more than this sentence, he was his own party and former secretary and challenger of Erdogan, Kemal Kilicdaroglu, to get his way to the presidential last year.
&nbsp;
A practicing Muslim, but a member of a secular party, this former entrepreneur with origins of the Black Sea, coming from a family who raised a great fortune in construction, managed to attract consensus among religious and builders. The origins and the family building company allowed him to be a man of doing so, to the point that one of the strengths of the electoral campaign was the numerous open yards and works inaugurated in these 5 years.
&nbsp;
Although both in 2019 and in these last elections he obtained the vote of many of the Kurds of Istanbul, Imamoglu does not seem to have a predilection for the largest minority of Turkey and avoids naming them explicitly. A mistake that in the past his party paid dearly. It is no coincidence that the Chp Republicans are practically absent. The pro-curdo party Dem, who joined him in 2019, criticized him for his silence when dozens of his officials had been removed from office and jailed. At the same time, accusations of xenophobia were not lacking when, especially in 2019, Imamoglu's campaign was centred on the "invasion of Syrian refugees" that jeopardized the secularity of Turkey.
&nbsp;
Several members of his own party accused him of being more interested in his career and being projected towards the presidency, at the expense of voters. Istanbul's first citizen armchair is the natural trampoline to drive the country. Erdogan, who, as mayor in the 1990s, set the ground for an ascent that saw him become prime minister and then president. The leap from the metropolis on the Bosphorus to the Turkish presidency is also reflected in the numbers of a city which, with a population of 16 million, counts more inhabitants than 20 of the 27 States of the European Union.&nbsp;

