AGI - The Japanese royal family is now on Instagram, but do not expect any selfies from its official account, launched today. The first 19 posts are photos and videos of official events depicting Emperor Naruhito and Empress Masako, intent on performing their royal duties during recent public appearances. A few hours after social debut as a public profile, the Imperial Household Agency account (Iha), announced a week ago but until now remained in "private" form, collected over 180,000 followers. The Japanese monarchy has mythological origins dating back to more than two millennia and any public criticism of the emperor remains a taboo in the country. Joining social media, the institution hopes to arouse interest among younger generations on what the imperial family does, explained a spokesman of the Iha. On Instagram no photos or information from behind the scenes of the imperial family: rigorously facts-based captions explain what the emperor did in what day, from meeting with foreign dignitaries to admiration of bonsai trees; even user comments to posts are carefully moderated by the account administration that so far does not follow any other user and has not ventured into Instagram stories.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Iha is on Instagram! I thought it was a April fish!" wrote an X user in reaction to the launch. Some users joked that it was good that the reals had chosen the most 'civilized' Instagram instead of X, ex Twitter. Naruhito rose to the throne of the Chrysanthemum in 2019 in a traditional ceremony after his father, very popular, became the first emperor to abdicate in over two centuries.
Other monarchies have created social media accounts, including British royals, which have recently been at the centre of a storm of complottist voices and theories. The manipulation of a family photo released from the palace to the media has fueled online speculations on the fate of Kate Middleton, Princess of Wales, who after days of mystery revealed to be sick of cancer.&nbsp;
